[!INFO] Parasitology of malaria
Plasmodium species are protozoans. (A subgroup of Apicomplexa)
The malaria parasites are unable to synthesize their own amino acids. So, they rely on breakdown of haemoglobin from RBCs to obtain their AA. The toxic haem group, which is a byproduct of this, is polymerized into non toxic hemozoin by the parasite.

Comparison of antimalarials

Source

[!TIP] Mnemonic
Artemether - 'ether' is non polar -> artemether is liphophilic -> therefore, not given IV.

see [[historyofAntimalarials.pdf]]

Chloroquine was probably the most effective antimalarial to date but this and it's low S/E profile led to it's abuse; it was even incorporated into table salt! -> this inevitably led to resistance; but so far, only falciparum has managed to develop resistance to it.

whereas most of the 'quinolone' nucleus based drugs came from the west, Artemisinin emerged from China during the Vietnam war. It's still very difficult to synthesize so supply remains reliant on extraction from natural sources.

Torsades de Pointes

[!INFO] Definition of Tosade de pointes
Torsade is defined as the combination of polymorphic ventricular tachycardia plus a prolonged QT-interval.
Source
Polymorphic VT is defined as ventricular tachycardia with varying QRS amplitute.

Pathophysiology: QT prolongation predisposes to 'after depolarizations' which can produce TdP


also [[torsadesDePointes.png]]

  • Life threatening arrhythmia
  • This is a type of polymorphic ventricular tachycardia.
  • QRS morphology changes from beat to beat like in any polymorphic VT.
  • Is inherently unstable -> either terminates within spontaneously or degenerates to VF
  • Associated with acquired or congenital prolonged QT.
    • for TdP to be diagnosed, the patient must have evidence of QT prolongation.
  • Can occur in hypokalemia
  • Group Ia antiarrthmics which prolong QT should never be used! (basically, disopyramide is contraindicated) [[Cardiology MCQ discussion#Antiarrhythmic drugs|Antiarrhtymics]]
Management
  1. Magnesium sulfate bolus (4g of MgSO4) even if Mg level is normal
  2. Correct all electrolytes
  3. Stop all QT prolonging medications
    1. Quinidine, disopyramide, flecainide, haloperidol, chlorpromazine, TCAs + many others

Systemic Lupus Erythematosus SLE

[!INFO] When to suspect SLE: typical case history

  • Young woman (of child bearing age)
  • presenting with fatigue, arthralgia, pleuritic chest pain,
  • hypertension
  • Malar rash (photosensitive)
  • Pleural friction rub (serositis)
  • Several tender and swollen joints
  • Mild peripheral oedema
  • Labs: leukopenia, anemia, Creatinine, albumin,
  • proteinuria, active urine sediment,
  • hypocomplmentemia, ANA+, dsDNA+, anti Ro, La and Smith
    Patients can also have alopecia, neurologic symptoms, Raynaud phenomenon, recurrent miscarriage

[!INFO] what is SLE?
lupus - skin wound like a wolf bite.
The term lupus was used indistinctively during the entire Middle Ages for a broad variety of ulcerative skin conditions predominant on the lowerlimbs

1790: lupus is listed among tuberculae and described as a nodular eruption of the face which develops into an ulceration.6 It is important to underline that until the middle of the 20th century, tens of thousands of lupus vulgaris cases, a form of cutaneous tuberculosis, existed in continental Europe

modern history being marked by the recognition of DNA as the main target of antinuclear antibodies and the central role of interferons.

SLE is a chronic inflammatory disease that can affect almost any organ system, although it mainly involves the skin, joints, kidneys, blood cells, and nervous system. Its presentation and course are highly variable, ranging from indolent to fulminant. - Medscape

Lupus can affect almost every organ, most prominently and devastatingly the kidney and the central nervous system (CNS). Source

The kidney is the most commonly involved visceral organ in SLE - Medscape.
about 50% develop clinically evident renal disease.

Overall, skin manifestations are probably the commonest organ involved.

components of the immune system, both cellular and humoral, are found in these target-organs (skin and kidney)

  • URT - Otitis (even hearing loss), bloody nasal discharge, crusting, oral or nasal ulcers.
  • LRT - hoarseness, dry cough, pleuritic chest pain, life threatening haemoptysis.
  • Kidney - rapidly proliferative glomerulonephritis. -> nephritic picture
  • Skin - purpura of lower extremeties.
  • hCG producing tumours are an import cause of gynaecomastia. hCG acts like LH to increase testosterone production. hCG levels should be done in the workup.

[!TIP] mnemonic: Drugs causing gynaecomastia
Gay DISCO

  1. Goserelin - Mechanism of Action Goserelin (a gonadotropin-releasing hormone [GnRH] analog) causes an initial increase in luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle stimulating hormone (FSH), chronic administration of goserelin results in a sustained suppression of pituitary gonadotropins
  2. Digoxin
  3. Isoniazide
  4. Spironolactone
  5. Cimetidine
  6. Oestrogen

Von hippel-lindau disease

#autosomalDominant
Hallmarks:
retinal and central nervous system (CNS) hemangioblastomas (blood vessel tumors), pheochromocytomas, multiple cysts in the pancreas and kidneys, and an increased risk for malignant transformation of renal cysts into renal cell carcinoma.

Source

Peutz-Jeghers syndrome

#autosomalDominant

  • Characterized by gastrointestinal (GI) polyposis, mucocutaneous pigmented macules, and predisposition to certain cancers. Patients with Peutz-Jeghers syndrome are at an increased risk for developing GI cancers of the colorectal, pancreatic, and gastric systems, in addition to a wide variety of non-GI epithelial malignancies including breast, uterine, cervical, lung, ovarian, and testicular cancers.
  • Commonest cancer is colorectal
  • Caused by mutations in STK11 tumour suppressor gene on chromosome 19
Gastric polyps mucocutaneous pigmentation
